\b\fs28\cf2 Introduction\par\b0\fs22\cf1\par
Deep learning, a subfield of machine learning and artificial intelligence, has revolutionized numerous industries in recent years. It involves training artificial neural networks with multiple layers (hence "deep") to learn complex patterns and representations from large datasets. Unlike traditional machine learning algorithms that rely on explicit feature engineering, deep learning models automatically learn hierarchical features, enabling them to tackle intricate problems with remarkable accuracy. This document provides a comprehensive overview of deep learning, exploring its fundamental concepts, architectures, applications, and challenges. We will delve into the intricacies of various deep learning models, including convolutional neural networks (CNNs) for image processing, recurrent neural networks (RNNs) for sequential data, and generative adversarial networks (GANs) for generating new data. Furthermore, we will discuss the computational requirements, ethical considerations, and future directions of this rapidly evolving field. The aim is to provide a solid understanding of deep learning's capabilities and limitations, equipping readers with the knowledge to assess its potential in diverse contexts. \par\par
\b\fs28\cf2 Neural Networks and Backpropagation\par\b0\fs22\cf1\par
At the heart of deep learning lies the artificial neural network. These networks are composed of interconnected nodes (neurons) organized in layers: an input layer, one or more hidden layers, and an output layer. Each connection between neurons has an associated weight, representing the strength of the connection. The network learns by adjusting these weights to minimize the difference between its predictions and the actual values in the training data. This process is achieved through backpropagation, an algorithm that calculates the gradient of the loss function with respect to the network's weights. The gradient indicates the direction of steepest descent in the loss landscape, guiding the weight updates. Different optimization algorithms, such as stochastic gradient descent (SGD) and Adam, are employed to efficiently navigate this landscape and find optimal weights. The choice of activation functions, which introduce non-linearity into the network, is crucial for its ability to learn complex patterns. Common activation functions include sigmoid, ReLU, and tanh, each with its own advantages and disadvantages. The depth of the network, i.e., the number of hidden layers, significantly impacts its capacity to learn intricate features and representations from data. \par\par
